PART 1
PRIVATE ZERO-KNOWLEDGE VAULT
Software Requirements Specification (SRS)
Version 1.0
SECTION 1 — PROJECT OVERVIEW
Objective

Build a production-grade private encrypted vault intended exclusively for two predefined users to securely store, organize, and access highly sensitive personal images.

This application is not a social platform, not a cloud gallery, and not a general file-sharing service.

Its primary objective is maximum privacy, confidentiality, integrity, and long-term security.

The system shall prioritize security over convenience in every architectural and implementation decision.

The application must be built as though it will be exposed to the public Internet and must assume that attackers will continuously attempt unauthorized access.

The application must follow a Zero-Knowledge security model wherever technically feasible.

The server must never have the ability to decrypt users' stored images.

SECTION 2 — CORE DESIGN PRINCIPLES

The implementation shall follow these principles without exception.

Privacy First

Every design decision must prioritize user privacy above convenience.

Zero Knowledge

The server must never possess encryption keys.

Images shall be encrypted inside the browser before upload.

Decryption shall happen only inside the browser after successful authentication.

The server stores only encrypted binary data.

Least Privilege

Every component shall receive only the permissions absolutely necessary.

No service, route, or API should have unnecessary privileges.

Defense in Depth

Assume individual security layers may eventually fail.

Multiple independent security mechanisms shall protect every sensitive resource.

Authentication alone is never considered sufficient.

Authorization must be verified on every protected request.

Secure by Default

Every feature shall default to the safest configuration.

Public access shall never be enabled by default.

Sharing shall never be enabled.

Directory browsing shall never be possible.

Fail Secure

Whenever unexpected behavior occurs, the application shall deny access rather than allow it.

