SECTION 4 — THREAT MODEL

The application shall assume the following attack scenarios.

External attacker

Attempts to:

Guess passwords
Enumerate users
Scan endpoints
Discover hidden routes
Access uploaded images directly
Exploit API endpoints
Brute force login
Exploit SQL Injection
Exploit XSS
Exploit CSRF
Exploit SSRF
Upload malicious files
Stolen URL

An attacker obtains an image URL.

Expected result:

The URL must be completely useless.

Without an authenticated session, the server must always respond:

401 Unauthorized

or

403 Forbidden

Never return image data.

Database Leak

Assume the database becomes public.

Expected result:

Passwords remain securely hashed.

Sensitive metadata remains encrypted.

Images remain encrypted.

No attacker can recover original images.

Storage Leak

Assume cloud storage becomes public.

Expected result:

Only encrypted files are exposed.

No plaintext image can be recovered.

Server Compromise

Assume an attacker gains read access to the server.

Expected result:

The attacker cannot decrypt stored images because encryption keys never exist on the server.

Session Hijacking

Assume session cookies are stolen.

Mitigation:

Short session lifetime.

Secure HTTP-only cookies.

SameSite Strict.

Automatic session invalidation.

Device management.

